Old Gods and continued strife, the Witchmen had found unity since their cultural dawn. In place of the wealth and comforts of the cities, the Witchmen valued their insights of the body, mind, and hedge magic. Eternal strife shaped their souls and no change but the one they fought for was necessary. The fruit of the world and a hand that could garden it gave their lives an irrevocable appeal they sought to defend.

Dissonance with the normalcy of other peoples was a working method, a mere component to their success. Dismissing the new pantheons and escaping the lure of a lax society, they felt themselves closer to the purpose of life than others. Deviance from the overwhelming beliefs surrounding them was ultimately a symptom, not a goal. Within their maxims, the concept of doubt was inexistent.

To the discontented among them deviancy was an ideology, a starved blade seeking to spill further profit from the world. What bled from the Witchmen's efforts before led to their lives now and what glory that was! Those of the new vision were no longer full from the lives they led and they tired of the whispered questions and secret meetings. A growing audacity taught them the concept of doubt. A new lust built the path to rid themselves of it.

Looking past morality, perversion made home on their tongues and the sickness of their sustenance became a welcomed poison. For every woe they consumed a new justification leapt forth from their mouths.

"Death becomes life in our methods."

The start of a ominous song became a phrase burnt daily into their hearts, changing the tune to which they beat.

Vague singsongs from a united force, they pulled their siblings together by deeming themselves an ascension of the old ways - an escape towards a future without strife. Old words were failing. Shrill screams of children as they witnessed the violation of their families fell silent to the new vision. Warriors halted in terror as their own kind sinned against the old unity and brought a new greed upon the flesh.


The tribes that remained scattered across the lands, warning their neighbors to avoid the monsters the rest of their kind had become. Method and symptom became ideology became symptom and method.
